The properly wraps every form of input and converts it from [:lower] to [:UPPER] always.
But we notice that this isn't applicable for numbers and special symbols. They are always untouched. 
Using our knowledge of shell we know that The thought process comes from understanding the Linux Process Tree.
When you log into an SSH session, the server starts a process. Usually, that process is /bin/bash. However, in your case, the server started a wrapper script (the "Uppercase Shell").
In Linux shell scripting, $0 is the variable that holds the name of the "calling" shell or the script itself. 
If you are inside a script named jail.sh, then $0 equals jail.sh. But if that script was executed by a shell, or if the shell is running interactively, 
$0 often points to the binary that started the environment.

